        <name>16.4.3 ln(1+x) approximation</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using the known result that \[\dfrac{1}{1+x}= {@ser1@} \qquad |x|&amp;lt;1,\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Find the first three terms in the approximation of \(\ln(1+x)\). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt; in the input box below, type "&lt;b&gt;log(x)&lt;/b&gt;" to represent \( \ln x \) (the natural logarithm of \(x\)). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Hint:&lt;/b&gt; integrate both sides of the expression. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\ln(1+x)\approx\) [[input:ans1]]&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-size: calc(0.90375rem + 0.045vw);"&gt;[[validation:ans1]]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: calc(0.90375rem + 0.045vw);"&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Use the expression to obtain an approximation to \(\ln({@var2@})\). &lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt; give your answer to &lt;b&gt;3 significant figures.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\ln({@var2@})\approx\) [[input:ans2]]&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-size: calc(0.90375rem + 0.045vw);"&gt;[[validation:ans2]]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: calc(0.90375rem + 0.045vw);"&gt;[[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Integrate both sides of \(\dfrac{1}{1+x}= {@ser1@} \, :\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[ \int \dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{1+x}= \ln(1+x)+c,\] where \(c\) is a constant of integration, and \[\int (1-x+x^2-\dots)\mathrm{d}x = x - \dfrac{x^2}{2} + \dfrac{x^3}{3} - \dots + k,\] where \(k\) is a constant of integration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we conclude \[\ln(1+x) +c = x - \dfrac{x^2}{2} + \dfrac{x^3}{3} - \dots + k \qquad \mathrm{if} \; |x|&amp;lt;1. \] &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choosing \(x=0\) shows that \(c=k\) so they cancel from this equation, therefore \[\ln(1+x) = x - \dfrac{x^2}{2} + \dfrac{x^3}{3} - \dots \qquad \mathrm{if} \; |x|&amp;lt;1.\]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now choose \(x = {@var1@}\) to approximate \(\ln(1+{@var1@}) = \ln({@var2@})\) using terms up to cubic: \[\ln({@var2@}) = {@var1@} - \dfrac{( {@var1@})^2}{2} + \dfrac{( {@var1@})^3}{3} - \dots \approx  {@ta2@}\] which is easily checked by a calculator.&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
